Iavan PIjoos, News24 Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Johannesburg &ndash; The case against terror accused twins Brandon-Lee and Tony-Lee Thulsie was postponed in the Johannesburg Magistrate's Court on Monday.&nbsp;National Prosecuting Authority spokesperson Phindi Louw said the case was postponed to November 15 for further investigation.&nbsp;The twins were arrested during raids in Newclare and Azaadville, on the West Rand, on July 9. They face three counts of contravening the Protection of Constitutional Democracy Against Terrorist and Related Activities Act.According to their charge sheet, the brothers, who were arrested along with siblings Ebrahim and Fatima Patel, were allegedly linked to ISIS. They were allegedly planning to set off explosives at a US embassy and "Jewish institutions" in South Africa.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.